 } } \right|$$<br><br>On applying $${C_1} \to {C_1} + {C_2} + {C_3}$$, $${C_2} \to {C_2} + {C_3}$$, we get<br><br>$$ = \left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; \alpha  &amp; {{\alpha ^2}}  \cr 
   1 &amp; \beta  &amp; {{\beta ^2}}  \cr 
   1 &amp; \gamma  &amp; {{\gamma ^2}}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>On applying $${R_1} \to {R_2} - {R_3}$$ and $${R_2} \to {R_2} - {R_3}$$ we get<br><br>$$ = \left| {\matrix{
   0 &amp; {(\alpha  - \beta )} &amp; {(\alpha  - \beta )(\alpha  + \beta )}  \cr 
   0 &amp; {(\beta  - \gamma )} &amp; {(\beta  - \gamma )(\beta  + \gamma )}  \cr 
   1 &amp; \gamma  &amp; {{\gamma ^2}}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>On taking common ($$\alpha$$ $$-$$ $$\beta$$) and ($$\beta$$ $$-$$ $$\alpha$$) from R<sub>1</sub> and R<sub>2</sub> respectively, we get<br><br>$$ = (\alpha  - \beta )(\beta  - \gamma )\left| {\matrix{
   0 &amp; 1 &amp; {\alpha  + \beta }  \cr 
